summary.md
     1â†’# SUMMARY.md
     3â†’The summary file is used by mdBook to know what chapters to include, in what
     4â†’order they should appear, what their hierarchy is and where the source files
     5â†’are. Without this file, there is no book.
     6â†’
     7â†’This markdown file must be named `SUMMARY.md`. Its formatting
     8â†’is very strict and must follow the structure outlined below to allow for easy
     9â†’parsing. Any element not specified below, be it formatting or textual, is likely
    10â†’to be ignored at best, or may cause an error when attempting to build the book.
    11â†’
    12â†’### Structure â€¦
    93â†’### Example â€¦
theme/README.md
     1â†’# Theme
     3â†’The default renderer uses a [handlebars](https://handlebarsjs.com) template to
     4â†’render your markdown files and comes with a default theme included in the mdBook
     5â†’binary.
     6â†’
     7â†’The theme is totally customizable, you can selectively replace every file from
     8â†’the theme by your own by adding a `theme` directory next to `src` folder in your
     9â†’project root. Create a new file with the name of the file you want to override
    10â†’and now that file will be used instead of the default file.
    11â†’
    12â†’Here are the files you can override:
    13â†’
    14â†’- **_index.hbs_** is the handlebars template.
    15â†’- **_head.hbs_** is appended to the HTML `<head>` section.
    16â†’- **_header.hbs_** content is appended on top of every book page.
    17â†’- **_css/_** contains the CSS files for styling the book.
    18â†’    - **_css/chrome.css_** is for UI elements.
    19â†’    - **_css/general.css_** is the base styles.
    20â†’    - **_css/print.css_** is the style for printer output.
    21â†’    - **_css/variables.css_** contains variables used in other CSS files.
    22â†’- **_book.js_** is mostly used to add client side functionality, like hiding /
    23â†’  un-hiding the sidebar, changing the theme, ...
    24â†’- **_highlight.js_** is the JavaScript that is used to highlight code snippets,
    25â†’  you should not need to modify this.
    26â†’- **_highlight.css_** is the theme used for the code highlighting.
    27â†’- **_favicon.svg_** and **_favicon.png_** the favicon that will be used. The SVG
    28â†’  version is used by [newer browsers].
    29â†’- **fonts/fonts.css** contains the definition of which fonts to load.
    30â†’  Custom fonts can be included in the `fonts` directory.
    31â†’
    32â†’Generally, when you want to tweak the theme, you don't need to override all the
    33â†’files. If you only need changes in the stylesheet, there is no point in
    34â†’overriding all the other files. Because custom files take precedence over
    35â†’built-in ones, they will not get updated with new fixes / features.
    36â†’
    37â†’**Note:** When you override a file, it is possible that you break some
    38â†’functionality. Therefore I recommend to use the file from the default theme as
    39â†’template and only add / modify what you need. You can copy the default theme
    40â†’into your source directory automatically by using `mdbook init --theme` and just
    41â†’remove the files you don't want to override.
    42â†’
    43â†’`mdbook init --theme` will not create every file listed above.
    44â†’Some files, such as `head.hbs`, do not have built-in equivalents.
    45â†’Just create the file if you need it.
    46â†’
    47â†’If you completely replace all built-in themes, be sure to also set
    48â†’[`output.html.preferred-dark-theme`] in the config, which defaults to the
    49â†’built-in `navy` theme.
    50â†’
    51â†’[`output.html.preferred-dark-theme`]: ../configuration/renderers.md#html-renderer-options
    52â†’[newer browsers]: https://caniuse.com/#feat=link-icon-svg
theme/editor.md
     1â†’# Editor
     3â†’In addition to providing runnable code playgrounds, mdBook optionally allows them
     4â†’to be editable. In order to enable editable code blocks, the following needs to
     5â†’be added to the ***book.toml***:
     6â†’
     7â†’```toml
     8â†’[output.html.playground]
     9â†’editable = true
    10â†’```
    11â†’
    12â†’After enabling editable code blocks, the `editable` attribute must be added to a
    13â†’code block to make it editable:
    14â†’
    15â†’~~~markdown
    16â†’```rust,editable
    17â†’fn main() {
    18â†’    let number = 5;
    19â†’    print!("{}", number);
    20â†’}
    21â†’```
    22â†’~~~
    23â†’
    24â†’The above will result in this editable playground:
    25â†’
    26â†’```rust,editable
    27â†’fn main() {
    28â†’    let number = 5;
    29â†’    print!("{}", number);
    30â†’}
    31â†’```
    32â†’
    33â†’Note the new `Undo Changes` button in the editable playgrounds.
    34â†’
    35â†’## Customizing the editor
    37â†’By default, the editor is the [Ace](https://ace.c9.io/) editor, but, if desired,
    38â†’the functionality may be overridden by providing a different folder:
    39â†’
    40â†’```toml
    41â†’[output.html.playground]
    42â†’editable = true
    43â†’editor = "/path/to/editor"
    44â†’```
    45â†’
    46â†’Note that for the editor changes to function correctly, the `book.js` inside of
    47â†’the `theme` folder will need to be overridden as it has some couplings with the
    48â†’default Ace editor.
theme/index-hbs.md
     1â†’# index.hbs
     3â†’`index.hbs` is the handlebars template that is used to render the book. The
     4â†’markdown files are processed to html and then injected in that template.
     5â†’
     6â†’If you want to change the layout or style of your book, chances are that you
     7â†’will have to modify this template a little bit. Here is what you need to know.
     8â†’
     9â†’## Data
    11â†’A lot of data is exposed to the handlebars template with the "context". In the
    12â†’handlebars template you can access this information by using
    13â†’
    14â†’```handlebars
    15â†’{{name_of_property}}
    16â†’```
    17â†’
    18â†’Here is a list of the properties that are exposed:
    19â†’
    20â†’- ***language*** Language of the book in the form `en`, as specified in `book.toml` (if not specified, defaults to `en`). To use in <code
    21â†’  class="language-html">\<html lang=\"{{ language }}\"></code> for example.
    22â†’- ***title*** Title used for the current page. This is identical to `{{ chapter_title }} - {{ book_title }}` unless `book_title` is not set in which case it just defaults to the `chapter_title`.
    23â†’- ***book_title*** Title of the book, as specified in `book.toml`
    24â†’- ***chapter_title*** Title of the current chapter, as listed in `SUMMARY.md`
    25â†’
    26â†’- ***path*** Relative path to the original markdown file from the source
    27â†’  directory
    28â†’- ***content*** This is the rendered markdown.
    29â†’- ***path_to_root*** This is a path containing exclusively `../`'s that points
    30â†’  to the root of the book from the current file. Since the original directory
    31â†’  structure is maintained, it is useful to prepend relative links with this
    32â†’  `path_to_root`.
    33â†’- ***previous*** and ***next*** These are objects used for linking to the previous and next chapter. They contain the properties `title` and `link` of the corresponding chapter.
    34â†’- ***chapters*** Is an array of dictionaries of the form
    35â†’  ```json
    36â†’  {"section": "1.2.1", "name": "name of this chapter", "path": "dir/markdown.md"}
    37â†’  ```
    38â†’  containing all the chapters of the book. It is used for example to construct
    39â†’  the table of contents (sidebar).
    40â†’
    41â†’## Handlebars helpers
    43â†’In addition to the properties you can access, there are some handlebars helpers
    44â†’at your disposal.
    45â†’
    46â†’### toc
    48â†’The toc helper is used like this
    49â†’
    50â†’```handlebars
    51â†’{{#toc}}{{/toc}}
    52â†’```
    53â†’
    54â†’and outputs something that looks like this, depending on the structure of your
    55â†’book
    56â†’
    57â†’```html
    58â†’<ul class="chapter">
    59â†’    <li><a href="link/to/file.html">Some chapter</a></li>
    60â†’    <li>
    61â†’        <ul class="section">
    62â†’            <li><a href="link/to/other_file.html">Some other Chapter</a></li>
    63â†’        </ul>
    64â†’    </li>
      â†’â€¦
    80â†’### resource
    82â†’The path to a static file.
    83â†’It implicitly includes `path_to_root`,
    84â†’and accounts for files that are renamed with a hash in their filename.
    85â†’
    86â†’```handlebars
    87â†’<link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ resource "css/chrome.css" }}">
    88â†’```
    89â†’
    90â†’### fa
    92â†’mdBook includes a copy of [Font Awesome Free's](https://fontawesome.com)
    93â†’MIT-licensed SVG files. It accepts three positional arguments:
    94â†’
    95â†’1. Type: one of "solid", "regular", and "brands" (light and duotone are not
    96â†’   currently supported)
    97â†’2. Icon: anything chosen from the
    98â†’   [free icon set](https://fontawesome.com/v6/search)
    99â†’3. ID (optional): if included, an HTML ID attribute will be added to the
   100â†’   icon's wrapping `<span>` tag
   101â†’
   102â†’For example, this handlebars syntax will become this HTML:
   103â†’
   104â†’```handlebars
   105â†’{{fa "solid" "print" "print-button"}}
   106â†’```
   107â†’
   108â†’```html
      â†’â€¦
theme/syntax-highlighting.md
     1â†’# Syntax highlighting
     3â†’mdBook uses [Highlight.js](https://highlightjs.org) with a custom theme
     4â†’for syntax highlighting.
     5â†’
     6â†’Automatic language detection has been turned off, so you will probably want to
     7â†’specify the programming language you use like this:
     8â†’
     9â†’~~~markdown
    10â†’```rust
    11â†’fn main() {
    12â†’    // Some code
    13â†’}
    14â†’```
    15â†’~~~
    16â†’
    17â†’## Supported languages
    19â†’These languages are supported by default, but you can add more by supplying
    20â†’your own `highlight.js` file:
    21â†’
    22â†’- apache
    23â†’- armasm
    24â†’- bash
    25â†’- c
    26â†’- coffeescript
    27â†’- cpp
    28â†’- csharp
    29â†’- css
    30â†’- d
    31â†’- diff
    32â†’- go
    33â†’- handlebars
    34â†’- haskell
    35â†’- http
    36â†’- ini
    37â†’- java
    38â†’- javascript
    39â†’- json
    40â†’- julia
    41â†’- kotlin
    42â†’- less
    43â†’- lua
    44â†’- makefile
    45â†’- markdown
    46â†’- nginx
    47â†’- nim
    48â†’- nix
    49â†’- objectivec
    50â†’- perl
    51â†’- php
    52â†’- plaintext
    53â†’- properties
    54â†’- python
    55â†’- r
    56â†’- ruby
    57â†’- rust
    58â†’- scala
    59â†’- scss
    60â†’- shell
    61â†’- sql
    62â†’- swift
    63â†’- typescript
    64â†’- x86asm
    65â†’- xml
    66â†’- yaml
    67â†’
    68â†’## Custom theme
    69â†’Like the rest of the theme, the files used for syntax highlighting can be
    70â†’overridden with your own.
    71â†’
    72â†’- ***highlight.js*** normally you shouldn't have to overwrite this file, unless
    73â†’  you want to use a more recent version.
    74â†’- ***highlight.css*** theme used by highlight.js for syntax highlighting.
    75â†’
    76â†’If you want to use another theme for `highlight.js` download it from their
    77â†’website, or make it yourself, rename it to `highlight.css` and put it in
    78â†’the `theme` folder of your book.
    79â†’
    80â†’Now your theme will be used instead of the default theme.
    81â†’
    82â†’## Improve default theme
    84â†’If you think the default theme doesn't look quite right for a specific language,
    85â†’or could be improved, feel free to [submit a new
    86â†’issue](https://github.com/rust-lang/mdBook/issues) explaining what you
    87â†’have in mind and I will take a look at it.
    88â†’
    89â†’You could also create a pull-request with the proposed improvements.
    90â†’
    91â†’Overall the theme should be light and sober, without too many flashy colors.
